</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">= Hot Cloning A Linux Disk While the OS Is Running =

I bought a new hard drive for my laptop, which has 2 drive bays. I use this to hold my OS disk and a large "storage" disk I share between Linux and Windows. But, just as easily, I can pull the storage drive out and use it to clone the primary drive.

== Disk Prep ==

# '''fdisk -l'''
# fire up gparted. 
# create a partition table on the new disk. ''msdos'' work for both Linux and Windows (it's the MRB partition).
# create a new partition ~500 megs in size with the 'boot' flag on /dev/sdb1
# create a new swap partition about equal to the RAM (8 gigs on Cowspot) on /dev/sdb2
# create a new ext4 partition at least as large as the existing linux partition on /dev/sdb3
# open a terminal
# '''nano /etc/fstab'''
# add /dev/sdb1 to the fstab as /mnt/boot
# add /dev/sdb3 to the fstab as /mnt/root
# '''mkdir /mnt/boot'''
# '''mkdir /mnt/root'''
# '''mount -a''' to refresh your fstab

Note: All partitions should be "primary".

Now that all partitions have been created, we can use the magic of rsync to sync while the system is up and running.

== Hot Cloning Using Rsync ==

# return to the terminal
# '''rsync -aAXvP / /mnt/root --exclude={"/dev/*","/proc/*","/sys/*","/boot/*","/tmp/*","/run/*","/mnt/*","/media/*",/lost+found}''' this copies everything important except the boot directory.
# '''rsync -aAXvP /boot/* /mnt/boot/'''
# return to gparted
# To clone windows: Select the windows partition, right click on the selection and choose copy. In the disk selection list choose the new disk. Select the free (unallocated space), right click and choose paste. Then just apply the operations. This will copy Windows.
# Select the new Windows partition and apply the 'boot' flag.
# After this you can add any leftover free space to either the windows or linux partition by choosing to 'resize' them in gparted.
# chroot into /mnt/root
# run grunb2 configuration: grub2-install /dev/sda &amp;&amp; grub2-mkconfig > /boot/grub/grub.cfg

The syncs can be done in any order as long as the partitions have already been created.

== Tidying Up ==

add notes here on how to clean up both fstabs (the old and new).
# '''nano /etc/fstab'''
#
#
# When booting into the new disk (both linux and windows) for the first time, make sure to allow any disk checking/correction to run and complete.

== Scratch Notes == 

For future updates/only using the command line.

# dd can be made to display a progress bar.
# '''yum install pv dialog''' and then '''(pv -n /dev/sda | dd of=/dev/sdb bs=128M conv=notrunc,noerror) 2>&amp;1 | dialog --gauge "Running dd command (cloning), please wait..." 10 70 0'''
